<H3> <TI>   MITI Official To Visit U.S., Discuss Trade </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    MITI Official To Visit U.S., Discuss Trade </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0705083094 Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database in Japanese 6 May 
94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0705083094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From MAINICHI SHIMBUN 7 May Morning Edition] </F>
  [Text] It is expected that in order to provide breakthrough 
in the deadlocked Japan-U.S. economic framework talks, Councilor 
Sozaburo Okamatsu of the Ministry of International Trade and 
Industry [MITI] will visit the United States early next week and 
hold unofficial negotiations with U.S. counterparts in charge of 
trade, a government source disclosed on 6 May. The source said 
that in unofficial negotiations, Okamatsu, in an attempt to seek 
ways to resume and reach an agreement on the Japan-U.S. economic 
framework talks before the industrialized nations meeting 
(Naples summit), will exchange opinions on macroeconomics 
policies designed to solve the issue of Japan's trade surplus 
and how to interpret and set up "objective criteria" for each 
trade sector. 
  Councilor Okamatsu, together with MITI Minister Eijiro Hata, 
is scheduled to attend a two-day East-West meeting of economic, 
industrial, and trade ministers to be held in Warsaw on 6-7 May. 
After the meeting, Councilor Okamatsu will fly straight to the 
United States. Although the main purpose of his U.S. visit is 
to deliver a lecture there, the government source said that, 
after the lecture, he plans to meet with U.S. officials such as 
Cutter, deputy chief of staff and assistant to the president (in 
charge of economic policies), who is a member of the National 
Economic Council (NEC) and is one of those who are in charge of 
trade affairs. 
  The Japan-U.S. economic framework talks have been deadlocked 
following the failure of the Japan-U.S. summit talks on 11 
February in concluding the economic framework talks. Former 
Foreign Minister (currently Prime Minister) Tsutomu Hata, in 
talks with U.S. Trade Representative Kantor in Morocco on 15 
April, confirmed that the two nations will make efforts to 
resume the economic framework talks. Moreover, in late April, a 
top MITI leader said: "There have been differences between the 
two nations in views on overall objective of the framework 
talks. If we discuss this matter, we will be able to find ways 
to resume the talks." In this way, the top official hinted that 
unofficial vice ministerial talks will be held after the May 
holidays. 
  A visit to the United States by MITI Councilor Okamatsu 
signifies that unofficial negotiations will virtually start. It 
is observed that with his negotiations as the start, 
behind-the-scenes unofficial negotiations involving the USTR 
will get under way, in hopes of resuming the economic framework 
talks before the Naples summit is held. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

