<H3> <TI>   Kakizawa Views U.S. Stand on Numerical Targets </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kakizawa Views U.S. Stand on Numerical Targets </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0805110994 Tokyo ASAHI SHIMBUN in Japanese 8 May 94 
Morning Edition p 9--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0805110994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo ASAHI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Hiroki Fukuda] </F>
  [Text] Damascus, 7 May -- Foreign Minister Koji Kakizawa 
held a meeting on 6 May with reporters, who are traveling with 
him, and commented on the Japan-U.S. new economic talks, saying: 
"As long as free economy and free trade are foundations of 
Japan and the United States, I think it is not logical for the 
United States to demand Japan to set numerical targets. I have 
a feeling that determining it is not logical to call for 
numerical targets, the United States is beginning to realize 
that such a demand will not gain support from the world opinion." 
  The foreign minister held a meeting with U.S. Secretary of 
State Christopher in Cairo on 3 May. According to the foreign 
minister, the secretary of state said at the meeting that "we 
are not demanding Japan to set numerical targets." It seems 
that the foreign minister's remarks were based on Christopher's 
comment. 

</TEXT>

