<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Australia Seeks Military Exchanges With Tokyo </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Australia Seeks Military Exchanges With Tokyo </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0705144894 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 7 May 94 
Morning Edition p 2--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0705144894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] At a time when the process of creating a dialogue 
framework for the security of the Asia Pacific region is in 
progress, it is learned that Australia has informally sounded 
out Japan about military exchanges with a proposal to have 
officers of the Self-Defense Forces study at Australia's 
military academy. In the Asia Pacific region, ASEAN members have 
been making brisk moves toward creating a regional security 
system following the end of the Cold War, and Australia's bid 
for exchanges with Japan in the defense area is interpreted as 
an indication that nations in the region are showing great 
interest in Japan not only in the economic area, but in the 
security area. 
  Australia has begun reviewing its post-Cold War security 
strategy. It has recently compiled a basic defense plan, 
analyzing that, "although U.S. influence on the security of the 
Asia Pacific region has waned, the military presence of China, 
Japan, and India in the region has grown." Australia is believed 
to have sounded out Japan about military exchanges between the 
two countries with the aim of making it clear that it also 
places importance on Asian nations in the security area. 
  Japan has responded to Australia's proposal by simply 
saying, 
"We will study" out of consideration for our position of 
attaching importance to relations with the United States. Japan, 
however, plans to make a final decision on the Australian 
proposal after analyzing the situation in the Asia Pacific 
region. 
  The Asia Pacific region has yet to build its own collective 
security system because of its ethnic and cultural diversity. 
With regard to multilateral dialogue for the regional security, 
the "ASEAN region forum" is set to hold its first session this 
year and it will be attended by ASEAN member nations' foreign 
ministerial conference, Japan, the United States, China, and 
Russia. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

