<H3> <TI>   `Nothing' Decided About Framework Schedule </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `Nothing' Decided About Framework Schedule </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0905064994 Tokyo KYODO in English 0626 GMT 9 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0905064994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, May 9 KYODO -- Nothing specific has been 
decided between Japan and the United States on ways to resume 
the stalled trade "framework" talks, a senior ministry of 
International Trade and Industry (MITI) official said Monday [9 
May]. 
  But Tokyo will use "every level of communication tools" to 
break the impasse over the bilateral trade talks, Hideaki 
Kumano, vice MITI minister, told a press conference. 
  Kumano said Tokyo and Washington have yet to fix a timetable 
and other details for an early resumption of the deadlocked 
framework negotiations. 
  Kumano denied speculation that vice MITI minister for 
international affairs Sozaburo Okamatsu, the chief Japanese 
trade negotiator for the framework talks, will meet high-ranking 
U.S. trade officials during his ongoing visit to the U.S. 
  Okamatsu is in the U.S. only to deliver a speech at a 
Chicago 
college, and will return home Thursday, Kumano said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

