<H3> <TI>   Defense Chief Backtracks on Collective Security </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Defense Chief Backtracks on Collective Security </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0905071294 Tokyo KYODO in English 0705 GMT 9 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0905071294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, May 9 KYODO -- Defense Agency Director 
General Atsushi Kanda on Monday [9 May] turned back from an 
earlier stance and said he will abide by a longtime 
interpretation by previous governments that the Constitution 
bans the country from being involved in collective security 
arrangements. 
  Kanda told a news conference that the coalition government 
"cannot avoid discussing the Constitution...but I would rather 
say Japan should act in accordance with the current 
constitutional interpretation." 
  Shortly after assuming the post of state minister for 
defense 
late last month, Kanda said Japan needs to apply a more flexible 
interpretation to the Constitution regarding the exercise of 
collective security arrangements. 
  Political sources said Kanda might have withdrawn the 
earlier 
remark out of respect to the No. 2 opposition party, the Social 
Democratic Party, which quit the coalition last month and 
opposed Kanda's proposal to revise the constitutional 
interpretation. 

</TEXT>

