<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, May 7 KYODO -- Newly-appointed Justice 
Minister Hiroshi Nakai is known as an advocate of environmental 
problems in the House of Representatives. 
  Nakai, a 51-year-old lower house legislator of the 
Democratic 
Socialist Party (DSP), replaced Shigeto Nagano, 71, Saturday 
after Nagano resigned over his remarks denying the 1937 Nanjing 
massacre and Japan's aggressive role in World War II. 
  Nakai has served as the DSP's deputy secretary general and 
as 
chairman of the lower house Committee on Commerce and Industry. 
  Nakai, born in the Chinese northeastern province of Jilin, 
was elected to the lower house for the first time in 1976 and 
has since been reelected six times from the No. 1 constituency 
of Mie Prefecture. Before embarking on his career as a 
politician, Nakai worked as a secretary for his father who was a 
lower house legislator of the Social Democratic Party. 

</TEXT>

