<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Sakigake, Seiun Form Joint Parliamentary Group </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Sakigake, Seiun Form Joint Parliamentary Group </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0905025294 Tokyo KYODO in English 0239 GMT 9 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0905025294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, May 9 KYODO -- New party Sakigake 
[Harbinger] and the group Seiun launched a unified 18-legislator 
parliamentary group in the House of Representatives on Monday [9 
May], party officials said. 
  Sakigake, the 15-legislator party, is headed by former Chief 
Cabinet Secretary Masayoshi Takemura in the preceding coalition 
government of former Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa, who lead 
his 37-member Japan New Party. 
  The three-legislator Seiun, a breakaway from the JNP, 
splintered after Hosokawa reneged on his promise to merge with 
Sakigake. Now, the new parliamentary bloc has emerged as the 
fifth largest parliamentary group in the lower house after the 
206-member Liberal Democratic Party, the 130-member Kaishin 
(Innovation), the 74-member Social Democratic Party and the 
52-legislator Komeito. 
  Takemura distanced his party from the coalition after 
Hosokawa decided to side with the chief coalition strategist 
Ichiro Ozawa, who is credited with sweeping his ally Tsutomu 
Hata to prime ministership in a policy reconciliation talk that 
led up to the April 25 Diet vote. 
  Ozawa and Takemura have confronted each other over the 
wisdom 
of proposals to expand Japan's parts [as received] in UN 
peacekeeping missions, hike the rate of the consumption tax, and 
taking a tougher line over the suspected North Korean nuclear 
arms program. 

</TEXT>

