<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   LDP, JCP Urge Hosokawa Testimony Over Loan </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    LDP, JCP Urge Hosokawa Testimony Over Loan </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0905100994 Tokyo KYODO in English 0956 GMT 9 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0905100994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, May 9 KYODO -- The Liberal Democratic Party 
(LDP) and the Japanese Communist Party (JCP) Monday [9 May] 
called for a Diet testimony by former Prime Minister Morihiro 
Hosokawa over a loan he received from a trucking company, 
resulting in a scandal that toppled him from office. The two 
parties made the demand at a preparatory meeting of the House of 
Representatives Budget Committee, claiming Hosokawa conceded 
that remarks he made before the Diet and the documents he 
presented concerning the loan included falsehood. 
  The LDP and the JCP also requested that three other persons, 
including Hosokawa's Secretary Namio Yatsuka, be summoned to the 
committee as witnesses over Hosokawa's shady fund management. 
  The 100 million yen Hosokawa borrowed from Sagawa Kyubin 
Co., 
a scandal-ridden trucking company, in 1982 created a Diet 
stalemate which led to his resignation last month. Hosokawa 
admitted in a press conference when he announced his resignation 
that he received the interest on the loan as a political 
contribution, partly revising his previous account that he had 
fully repaid the loan with interest. 
  In connection with the fund management problem, Hosokawa's 
secretary said last month that his private office had failed to 
report investment profits of 29 million yen to tax authorities. 
Chief Cabinet Secretary Hiroshi Kumagai, however, hinted at a 
press conference Monday [9 May] that the ruling coalition is not 
enthusiastic about summoning Hosokawa before the Diet. 
  An executives' meeting of the upper house's budget committee 
later decided to summon financial consultant Shuzo Fujiki before 
the committee Wednesday as a witness in Hosokawa's alleged 
involvement in the 1986 purchase of shares in telecommunications 
giant Nippon Telegraph and Telephone Corp. 
  The committee will formalize the decision in a meeting 
Tuesday. 
  Hosokawa has denied he was personally involved in the 
transaction, saying the deal was conducted by his late 
father-in-aw, although he has admitted he provided collateral 
for a loan from a stock investment firm to finance the purchase. 
  Opposition lawmakers claim Hosokawa used his position as a 
regional governor to secure the loan under favorable conditions. 
  Fujiki has said at a press conference he arranged the loan 
for Hosokawa and that it was his own deal. 
  The opposition camp apparently hopes Fujiki's testimony will 
force the ruling coalition to allow Hosokawa himself to be 
called before the committee and eventually force the former 
premier to resign as a member of the Diet. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-52167 </DOCNO>
