<H3> <TI>   Sumitomo Allegedly Paid Rightist 140 Million Yen </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Sumitomo Allegedly Paid Rightist 140 Million Yen </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0905121894 Tokyo KYODO in English 1144 GMT 9 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0905121894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, May 9 KYODO -- Sumitomo Heavy Industries 
Ltd. allegedly paid 140 million yen to the president of an 
Osaka-based rightist organization as a fee for settling the 
company's trouble with another rightist group over the 
construction of an incinerator, industry sources said Monday [9 
May]. 
  The sources said the major shipbuilder in the Sumitomo 
conglomerate made a consultant contract with a company run by 
the head of the rightist group in Osaka Prefecture, after the 
shipbuilder won a contract last August to build the incinerator 
in Tsukuba, Ibaraki Prefecture. The company paid 140 million 
yen into the account of the company run by the rightist under 
the name of a consultation fee, the sources said. 
  Rumors of bid-rigging surrounded the incinerator project and 
another rightist group had criticized the bid from a truck 
equipped with loudspeakers near Tsukuba's City Hall and at the 
mayor's house in late November last year, just before the 
ceremony to begin building the incinerator. 
  The president of the rightist group which made the 
consultant 
contract with Sumitomo Heavy Industries requested the other 
rightist group to stop its criticisms at that time, according to 
the sources. 
  A public relations official of Sumitomo Heavy Industries 
refused to comment on the allegations. 

</TEXT>

