<H3> <TI>   Reactions to Caning Peter Fay Continue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reactions to Caning Peter Fay Continue </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Affect on U.S. Ties Discussed </H4>

<F P=102> BK0605113794 Singapore Singapore Broadcasting Corporation in 
English 1100 GMT 6 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK0605113794 </F>
<F P=104>  Singapore Singapore Broadcasting Corporation </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Foreign Ministry says it believes that ties 
between Singapore and the United States are robust enough to 
weather any difficulties caused by Michael Fay's caning. A 
Ministry spokesman says he hopes both sides would focus on their 
larger mutual interests and put this incident behind them. He 
said the United States and Singapore have always enjoyed the 
strong relationship based on many common interests and shared 
strategic objectives. The spokesman said it would be 
regrettable if the action of one individual who transgressed 
Singapore law and had been punished according to the law were 
allowed to affect bilateral relations. 
  The spokesman was responding to a statement by the acting 
spokesman for the U.S. State Department, Christine Shell. The 
statement was issued after a meeting between Assistant Secretary 
of State Winston Lord and Singapore Ambassador S.R. Nathan. The 
statement noted Mr. Lord said the incident would have to be 
taken into account in the overall relationship between the U.S. 
and Singapore. 

</TEXT>

