<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Radio Reports 6 May U.S., ROK `War Exercise' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Radio Reports 6 May U.S., ROK `War Exercise' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK0805044494 Pyongyang Korean Central Broadcasting Network 
in Korean 2213 GMT 7 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> SK0805044494 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang Korean Central Broadcasting Network 
in Korean 2213 GMT 7 May 94 </F>

<F P=105> Korean </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The U.S. imperialists and South Korean puppets 
conducted a war exercise for a Northward invasion and aerial 
espionage. 
  According to military sources, on 6 May, the U.S. 
imperialists dragged squadrons of fighter planes from its 
overseas bases into the skies above South Korea and conducted 
again a provocative aerial war exercise for a Northward invasion. 
  That day, the squadrons of fighter bombers and 
pursuit-assault planes that moved out from U.S. bases in the 
Pacific area to the skies above Yongwol, Pyongchang, Taejon, and 
Yechon frantically waged a surprise attack exercise against 
strategic targets in the Northern half of the Republic. 
  Mobilized to this war exercise were those airplane squadrons 
from overseas bases and some 180 various fighter bombers, 
assault planes, observation planes, and reconnaissance planes of 
the U.S. occupation Air Force in South Korea and of the puppet 
Air Force. 
  This frantic war exercise under the command of E-3 airborne 
warning and control planes that flew from a base in Okinawa, 
Japan was aimed at examining the practicality [hyonsilsong] of 
cooperation among airplane squadrons from overseas bases, the 
U.S. occupation Air Force in South Korea, and the puppet Air 
Force; and examining their capability of making a surprise 
attack for a Northward invasion. 
  On the same day, An RC-135 tactical reconnaissance plane 
flew 
from an overseas base into the skies above the area near the DMZ 
and then carried out electronic reconnaissance on strategic 
points in the northern half of the Republic while flying at a 
high altitude for a long time. 
  At the same time, A P-3 off-the-shelf aircraft [panjamgi] 
belonging to the Seventh U.S. Fleet flew into the skies above 
the East Sea of South Korea and then ran wild in carrying out 
espionage on our side's coastline and sea. A U-2 high-altitude 
strategic reconnaissance plane madly photographed and carried 
out electronic reconnaissance on areas in the Northern half of 
the Republic while flying day and night in the skies above an 
area near the Military Demarcation Line [MDL]. 
  In the meantime, the South Korean puppets were frenzied in 
firing bombs near the MDL in the Demilitarized Zone [DMZ], as 
well as increasing armed troops there. On 6 May, the South 
Korean puppets mobilized and deployed several tens of 
large-caliber gun units in Kumsan-ri, Puju county, with their 
barrels turned toward Songdong- ri, a western area of the front 
line in front of us, and moved hundreds of rascals with heavy 
arms [chungmujang aktangdul] forward from Hyon-ri, Imje county, 
an eastern area of the front line, and deployed them in an area 
adjacent to the DMZ. 
  On the same day, after occupying firing positions at 
Chongja-ri in Paju county and Kangnae-ri in Yonchon county, the 
puppet Army's large-caliber artillery units showed off a war 
frenzy by firing tens of bombs at an area near the DMZ. 
  These war maneuvers are a grave challenge to detent and 
peace 
on the Korean peninsula. 

</TEXT>

