<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Radio Cites Spokesman on Nagano Remarks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Radio Cites Spokesman on Nagano Remarks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK0705225994 Pyongyang Korean Central Broadcasting Network 
in Korean 2112 GMT 7 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> SK0705225994 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang Korean Central Broadcasting Network 
in Korean 2112 GMT 7 May 94 </F>

<F P=105> Korean </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] A spokesman for the DPRK Foreign Ministry, asked by 
a KCNA today to comment on the Japanese justice minister's 
recent outburst defending Japan's past aggression, said: 
  To the great consternation and resentment of the Korean 
people, Asian countries and the world public, Japan's Justice 
Minister Shigeto Nagano in an interview with the MAINICHI 
SHIMBUN newspaper 3 May said the Pacific war was not a war of 
aggression and the Nanjing Massacre was a "hoax." 
  Dismayed at the strong protest of public opinion at home and 
abroad, he called a "press conference" Friday to "revoke" and 
"apologize" for what he had said. However, it is no use crying 
over spilled milk. 
  The official statement of a country's justice minister 
cannot 
be regarded as a mistake. It reflects the political climate of 
Japan embodying militarism. 
  It has been nearly half a century since the end of World War 
II, but the Japanese authorities are trying to whitewash the 
past crimes and defend militarism, far from properly liquidating 
the past. This clearly shows they still have the old dream of 
"the Greater East Asia Co-Prosperity Sphere" for which they 
cried out during the Pacific war of aggression. 
  We cannot but take a serious view of the outburst because it 
came at a time when the Japanese authorities were intensifying 
their repressing and destroying maneuver [tanap malsal 
chaektong] against the General Association of Korean Residents 
in Japan as never before over the "nuclear issue" of the DPRK 
and undisguisedly resorting to the anti-DPRK campaign such as 
legal study to cope with the case of emergency on the Korean 
peninsula and debate on constitutional revision. 
  This proves that Japanese militarism has revived and plans 
to 
realize its aggressive design by force of arms and regards the 
Korean peninsula as the first target. 
  It is crystal-clear how dangerous it is for Japan obsessed 
with militarism and revanchism to work hard to take a permanent 
membership in the UN Security Council allegedly for its 
"international contribution." 
  The Asian peoples, who have fallen victim to Japanese 
imperialism in the past, and the peaceloving peoples of the 
world must pay due attention to and take precautions against 
reviving Japanese militarism. Japan must clearly know that 
militarist revival will lead to its own grave. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

