<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Pakistani Parties Support Ministry Statement </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Pakistani Parties Support Ministry Statement </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK0605001194 Pyongyang KCNA in English 1507 GMT 5 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0605001194 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Pyongyang, May 5 (KCNA) -- Eight political parties 
and organizations of Pakistan including the National Party, the 
People's Democratic Party and the Pakistan organization for 
Afro-Asian people's solidarity issued a joint statement on April 
24 supporting the April 20 memorandum of the Foreign Ministry of 
the Democratic People's Republic of Korea that clarified the 
main obstacle to the solution of the nuclear issue of the Korean 
peninsula and its background. 
  The statement sharply condemned the United States and the 
International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) for demanding a total 
inspection of the DPRK in a sinister attempt to stamp out its 
political system, ignoring the special position of the DPRK that 
suspended temporarily the effectuation of its withdrawal from 
the Nuclear Nonproliferation Treaty (NPT). 
  "We are convinced that the DPRK Government is showing 
fidelity with regard to the nuclear policy and highly estimate 
the DPRK Government for sincerely implementing the DPRK-U.S. 
agreement and pushing ahead with nuclear development under the 
strict surveillance of the IAEA. 
  "We castigate the IAEA Secretariat and the UN Security 
Council for openly applying the double-standard to the nuclear 
issue under the baton of the United States," the statement said, 
and stressed: "We warmly hail the declaration of the great 
leader President Kim Il-song that the DPRK neither has nuclear 
weapons nor needs to manufacture them." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

