Daily Report 
<DATE1>  6 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Meeting Marks Anniversary of World Peace Council </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Meeting Marks Anniversary of World Peace Council </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK0605125094 Pyongyang KCNA in English 1115 GMT 6 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0605125094 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Pyongyang, May 6 (KCNA) -- A meeting of peace 
champions and a photo exhibition were held in Pyongyang on May 6 
under the sponsorship of the Korean National Peace Committee on 
the occasion of the 45th anniversary of the founding of the 
World Peace Council. 
  Chong Chun-ki, chairman of the Committee for Cultural 
Relations with Foreign Countries and chairman of the Korean 
National Peace Committee, made a report, which was followed by 
speeches. 
  The reporter and speakers estimated the role and 
achievements 
of the world peace council in the 45-year long endeavours to 
strengthen and develop the struggle of peaceloving people all 
over the world and elaborated on the major tasks to promote the 
world peace movement and ways for their fulfilment. 
  They highly appreciated the world peace council for 
expressing firm solidarity with the Korean people in their 
struggle to achieve the reunification of the country. 
  They strongly urged that the United States stop its 
unjustifiable rackets to put pressure on and stifle the DPRK and 
accede to dialogue and negotiation for a fair solution to the 
nuclear issue on the Korean peninsula. 
  Considering it necessary to replace the Armistice Agreement 
with a peace one and make a peace arrangement in place of the 
present armistice body in order to remove the hostility between 
the DPRK and the United States, achieve reconciliation between 
them and ensure genuine peace and security on the Korean 
peninsula because the Military Armistice Agreement [as received] 
has been reduced to a mere sheet of paper and the Korean 
Armistice Commission [as received] turned into a nominal 
organisation by the unwarrantable acts of the United States, 
they expressed full support to the recent proposal of the DPRK 
Government concerning this. 
  An appeal to the peaceloving people of the world was adopted 
at the meeting. 
  It called upon all the people who value world peace and 
security to firmly unite as one irrespective of differences in 
political views and religious belief and turn out in the 
struggle to build an independent and peaceful, new world freed 
from domination and subordination, aggression and war. 
  It said: 
  After its foundation, the World Peace Council has made a lot 
of contributions to achieving national independence and social 
progress against imperialism, colonialism, neo-colonialism and 
racism, averting war and ensuring a durable peace and security 
of the world. 
  We remember the fact that it expressed full support and 
solidarity for the struggle of the Korean people to defend the 
freedom and independence of the country against the armed 
invasion by the imperialist allied forces and achieve the 
independent and peaceful reunification of the divided country. 
  To resolve the Korean question in a peaceful way is urgent 
in 
ensuring a durable peace and security in Asia and the Pacific. 
  We urge the United States to abandon its hostile policy to 
stifle Korea, the old policy of the Cold War era, and observe 
the principles already agreed on between the DPRK and the U.S. 
sides and promptly accede to the proposed DPRK-USA dialogue and 
negotiation intended to solve the nuclear issue of the Korean 
peninsula in a peaceful and fair way, replace the Korean 
armistice agreement with a peace one and make a new peace 
arrangement in place of the present armistice body. 
  We express the conviction that the world peace forces would 
continue to extend positive support and solidarity to the Korean 
people in their struggle to achieve the reunification of the 
country by means of confederacy based on one nation, one state, 
two systems and two governments on the three principles of 
independence, peaceful reunification and great national unity as 
agreed upon by the North and the South of Korea. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

