<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   PRC Cites DPRK `Pledge' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    PRC Cites DPRK `Pledge' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK0905005394 Seoul YONHAP in English 0042 GMT 9 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0905005394 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, May 9 (YONHAP) -- North Korean President Kim 
Il- song promised Chinese leader Deng Xiaoping in 1991 that 
Pyongyang would not develop nuclear weaponry, the MAINICHI 
SHIMBUN reported from San Francisco on Monday. 
  The newspaper quoted a senior U.S. official as saying that 
Kim clearly told Deng his country had neither the intention nor 
ability to develop nuclear arms during a visit to China in 
October 1991. Based on this pledge, China is continuing to 
respect North Korea's position until it can be proven that 
Pyongyang broke its promise. 
  China notified South Korean President Kim Yong-sam, during 
his trip to Beijing last March, and the U.S. Government of Kim 
Il-song's nuclear promise. Beijing also informed the two nations 
that it would take decisive action if Pyongyang broke its 
promise, according to the paper. 
  Senior Chinese leaders told President Kim Yong-sam that they 
opposed international sanctions against North Korea and asked 
Kim to understand their position, MAINICHI said. The newspaper 
said the Chinese emphasized to South Korea's president that "if 
things that impair the honor of China happen, then China will 
take decisive action." The paper noted that China also explained 
its basic position to Robert Gallucci, U.S. assistant secretary 
for political and military affairs, during his recent visit to 
China. The Chinese leaders told Gallucci that it was too early 
to prepare sanctions against North Korea. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

