<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Prime Minister Chairs Meeting on DPRK Policy </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Prime Minister Chairs Meeting on DPRK Policy </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK0705091994 Seoul YONHAP in English 0912 GMT 7 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0705091994 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, May 7 (YONHAP) -- The government and the 
ruling Democratic Liberal Party (DLP) held a policy coordination 
meeting on Saturday to decide to continue efforts to solve the 
North Korean nuclear problem through dialogue. 
  The meeting, attended by Prime Minister Yi Yong-tok, DLP 
Chairman Kim Chong-pil and other government and party officials, 
also decided to study measures to be taken when the efforts 
through dialogue fail, officials said. 
  The meeting confirmed the position that the government 
respects the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA)'s 
decision on the technical issues of the inspection of the North 
Korean nuclear sites and observation of the replacement of fuel 
rod of the five megawatt nuclear reactor in Yongbyon in North 
Korea. 
  But if North Korea replaces the fuel rod without observation 
of the IAEA, suspension of the North Korean-U.S. talks is 
inevitable, the meeting reaffirmed the position. 
  The government and the ruling party discussed another issue 
of the North Korean loggers. 
  The senior officials decided to have close consultation with 
the Russian Government on the North Koreans who escaped from the 
Siberian logging camps to solve the problem in an early date. 
  They will study ways to invite international organizations 
to 
intervene in the problem in an effort to prevent possible 
diplomatic trouble with Russia. 
  Meanwhile, the government and the ruling party will reject 
the North Korean proposal to replace the 1953 Armistice 
Agreement with a peace treaty with the United States alone, 
according to officials. 
  They reaffirmed that the Military Armistice Commission and 
the Neutral Nations Supervisory Commission should continue to 
exist. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

