<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Seoul, Japanese Shipbuilding Figures Compared </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Seoul, Japanese Shipbuilding Figures Compared </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK0705023494 Seoul YONHAP in English 0136 GMT 7 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0705023494 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, May 7 (YONHAP) -- Korean shipbuilders, even 
though they have won fewer ship orders than their Japanese 
rivals this year, are excelling in terms of price per tonnage of 
ships ordered, the Trade, Industry and Energy Ministry said 
Saturday. 
  In January-March, Korean shipbuilders received orders for 
1,011,000 tons at 1.2 billion U.S. dollars, amounting to 1,196 
dollars per tonnage. 
  Japanese shipbuilders received orders for 2,969,000 tons at 
3.06 billion dollars for 1,032 dollars per tonnage. 
  With orders received in April added, Korean shipbuilders 
posted 1,299 dollars per tonnage in the first four months, while 
the data for Japanese shipbuilders in April are not available 
yet. 
  Korean shipbuilders, who secured enough orders for the 
coming 
two years already last year, have sought to win relatively more 
profitable orders since the turn of the year, while their 
Japanese competitors have employed a low-price strategy. 
  At the price per tonnage, Korea topped Japan by 837 dollars 
to 704 dollars in 1990; however, Korea lagged behind Japan with 
1,023 dollars to 1,130 dollars in 1991, and with 1,143 dollars 
to 1,513 dollars in 1992. 
  Last year, Korean shipbuilders received orders for 9,519,000 
tons at 7.35 billion dollars for 772 dollars compared with 1,231 
dollars for Japanese shipbuilders. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

