<H3> <TI>   Foreign Sailors Allowed To Disembark, Embark </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Sailors Allowed To Disembark, Embark </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK0905130994 Seoul YONHAP in English 1145 GMT 9 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0905130994 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, May 9 (YONHAP) -- The government has 
liberalized disembarking and embarking in the country by foreign 
seamen including Korean-Chinese crews, the maritime and port 
administration reported on Monday. An official of the 
administration said foreign seamen can now disembark at South 
Korean ports with short-term visas only. 
  In the past, Korean-Chinese seamen were prohibited from 
disembarking in the country in fear that they may illegally find 
jobs while landing. To facilitate the new step, the government 
has prepared a guideline for the issuance of visas to foreign 
seamen for implementation retroactive to May 1. It replaces the 
guideline for the issuance of visas to Chinese seamen. 
  Presently a total of 951 foreign seamen work at Korean-flag 
freighters and fishing boats. 

</TEXT>

