<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Trade Minister Promises Reply to U.S. Demands </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Trade Minister Promises Reply to U.S. Demands </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0605172594 Tokyo KYODO in English 1536 GMT 6 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0605172594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Warsaw, May 6 KYODO -- Japan will soon reply to 
U.S. demands for further proposals to reduce its heavy trade 
surplus, Japan's trade minister promised U.S. Commerce Secretary 
Ron Brown in a meeting in Warsaw on Friday [6 May]. 
  Japanese International Trade and Industry Minister Eijiro 
Hata and Brown had a brief talk while they were here for a 
meeting of economic, industry and trade ministers from the Group 
of Seven (G-7) industrialized states and 10 former East Bloc 
nations. 
  Brown expressed a wish to reach a common understanding with 
Japan on the three points raised by U.S. Trade Representative 
Mickey Kantor in Marrakech last month -- that Japan take steps 
on both the macroeconomic and sectoral levels and set "objective 
criteria" to reduce its trade surplus, Japanese officials said. 
  Such an understanding is a prerequisite to the resumption of 
talks with Japan on a new bilateral trade framework, the U.S. 
secretary said, according to the officials. 
  Hata replied that he understands the importance of the three 
points and Japan wishes to see the issue settled in a way that 
would not lead to "managed trade," the officials said. 
  The Japanese minister indicated that efforts will be made to 
resume the trade framework talks ahead of an upcoming summit 
meeting of the G-7 countries in Naples, Italy, in July. 
  In a separate meeting with Russian Deputy Premier Aleksandr 
Shokhin the same day, Hata said Japan will continue support for 
Russia in its efforts for reform. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

