<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Saito: Resumption of Trade Talks Still Unclear </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Saito: Resumption of Trade Talks Still Unclear </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0905085694 Tokyo KYODO in English 0847 GMT 9 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0905085694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, May 9 KYODO -- Japan has not yet made any 
breakthrough with the United States to reopen the stalled 
"framework" trade talks, a senior Finance Ministry official said 
Monday [9 May]. 
  "Foreign Ministry officials are seeking possibilities 
through 
various channels, but there seems to be no clear direction yet," 
Vice Finance Minister Jiro Saito told a regular news conference. 
But he reiterated that substantial progress has been made in 
insurance which his ministry is in charge of negotiating among 
the three priority areas under the framework talks. 
  Other areas are automobiles and auto parts, and government 
procurement of medical and telecommunications equipment. 
  In a related development, a senior Foreign Ministry official 
said Foreign Minister Koji Kakizawa may visit the United States 
in late May or early June for talks with U.S. officials on ways 
to resume the framework talks. 
  "I hope that working-level talks will be resumed by the 
Middle of this month," the official, who declined to be named, 
told reporters. 
  The official said Kakizawa hopes to meet with U.S. leaders 
to discuss other delicate issues such as the suspected nuclear 
weapons development program by North Korea. 
  The official also said Kakizawa is likely to meet U.S. Trade 
Representative Mickey Kantor in Paris when they attend a 
ministerial session of the Organization for Economic Cooperation 
and Development (OECD) opening June 7. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

