<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hata To `Continue' Hosokawa's Economic Policies </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Hata To `Continue' Hosokawa's Economic Policies </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1005040394 Tokyo KYODO in English 0350 GMT 10 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1005040394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, May 10 KYODO -- Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata 
told his cabinet Tuesday [10 May] he will continue the economic 
policies of the Hosokawa cabinet, pursuing economic reforms 
through wide-ranging deregulation, government officials said. 
  Hata, who took over as prime minister April 28 to replace 
Morihiro Hosokawa, also told a cabinet meeting that he will seek 
to secure sustained economic growth by stimulating domestic 
demand, the officials said. 
  Hata also emphasized the need to implement the government's 
economic stimulation package adopted in February, obtain Diet 
approval of the fiscal 1994 budget, expedite compilation of 
economic deregulation plans and to do everything possible to 
implement tax reform before the end of the year, the officials 
said. 
  Koshiro Ishida, director general of the Management and 
Coordination Agency, told the meeting that he intends to have a 
government task force in charge of administrative reforms work 
out specific deregulation plans in June. 
  Regarding Japan's current account surplus, Chief Cabinet 
Secretary Hiroshi Kumagai told reporters there are signs that 
the surplus is beginning to subside. 
  Kumagai noted that the fiscal 1993 surplus, measuring goods, 
services and some unilateral transfers such as grant aid, 
decreased in yen terms for the first time in three years. He 
also said the dollar-based surplus in March dropped from a year 
earlier. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

