<F P=100> Vietnam </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hanoi Meeting Marks Dien Bien Phu Victory </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Hanoi Meeting Marks Dien Bien Phu Victory </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK0605152594 Hanoi VNA in English 1458 GMT 6 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> BK0605152594 </F>
<F P=104>  Hanoi VNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Hanoi VNA May 6 -- A grand meeting was held here 
today to mark the 40th anniversary of the Dien Bien Phu battle - 
most resounding victory of the Vietnam Army over the French 
expeditionary force (May 7, 1954). 
  Prominent among those present at the event were party 
General 
Secretary Do Muoi, President Le Duc Anh, Prime Minister Vo Van 
Kiet National Assembly Chairman Nong Duc Manh, and General Vo 
Nguyen Giap, former commander-in-chief of the VPA and commander 
of the Dien Bien Phu battle. 
  In the key-note speech at the meeting, Prime Minister Vo Van 
Kiet said: 'The Dien Bien Phu victory entered into the history 
of the Vietnamese people as a bach dang, a chi lang, and a dong 
da battle in the 20th century, a golden marker in the 
thousand-year history of building and defending the nation, a 
real and legendary exploit in the Ho Chi Minh time. 
  That is an ever lasting pride of the Vietnamese people, a 
source of encouragement to all nations in struggle for national 
independence, freedom and the human values'. 
  The prime minister pointed out that the Dien Bien Phu 
victory was made from the braveness and growth of the whole 
nation, the correctness of the revolutionary line, the vitality 
new regime, new society and new state in face of war challenges, 
the strength of the Peoples Armed Forces and the international 
support which the Vietnamese people remember and for which they 
were grateful to forever. 
  The victory, he said, is heritage of the national tradition, 
the development of the august revolution, and the crown of the 
first war of resistance. 
  The prime minister said that the Vietnamese people were 
launching a new struggle for prosperity, happiness and social 
justice. 
  Prime Minister Vo Van Kiet said he strongly believed that 
the Vietnamese people would push up the current process of 
renovation and development to steady success. 
  After reaffirming Vietnam's persistent foreign policy of 
being friends with all countries in the world, Prime Minister 
Kiet noted: 'After Dien Bien Phu especially in recent years, the 
relations between Vietnam and France has clearly entered into a 
new period. The multi-faceted cooperation between the two 
countries has proved that when the two parties have mutual 
understanding and goodwill, they could totally close their past 
pages to develop their normal fine relations. 
  The prime minister called on the entire nation to 
concentrate on building the country as well as the tasks of 
defending national independence, sovereignty, territorial 
integrity and national security. 'We should exert our efforts 
in strengthening the people's army, the people's security force 
and other people's armed forces to ensure that they would always 
play their key role together with the entire people, to firmly 
defend the airspace, the sea, and the territory, including the 
islands of our motherland', the prime minister stressed. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

