<F P=100> Thailand </F>
<H3> <TI>   Finance Chief on IMF Inflation Measures Call </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Finance Chief on IMF Inflation Measures Call </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK0905094094 Bangkok THE NATION in English 9 May 94 p B1, B2 </F>
<F P=103> BK0905094094 </F>
<F P=104>  Bangkok THE NATION </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Finance Minister Tharin Nimmanhemin stressed 
that it is not yet necessary to use monetary measures to curb 
inflation because the Bank of Thailand is still able to ensure 
the inflation rate does not exceed 4.5 per cent this year. 
  In an interview with THE NATION, Tharin responded to an 
International Monetary Fund (IMF) suggestion urging the Thai 
government to cautiously deal with possible high inflation. 
Tharin said that the Bank of Thailand is still able to "fine 
tune" the economy. Moreover, the Finance Ministry has 
maintained discipline in government's spending, he said. 
  He said that he got an assurance from the Bank of Thailand 
that the inflation rate would not exceed 4.5 per cent by the end 
of this year. Although the inflation rate in the first quarter 
was 4.8 per cent, Tharin said that the rate increased by only 
3.7 per cent over the past 12 months. In the first quarter of 
1993, the inflation rate rose by 3.3 percent over the previous 
year. 
  Tharin attributed the 5 percent inflation rate in January to 
the rise in farm prices. The central bank has already informed 
him that farm prices will be soon reduced, he noted. 
  "The IMF suggestion came as result of the brief observation 
from two or three IMF staffers who visited Thailand only for a 
few days. At any rate, the Finance Ministry and the Bank of 
Thailand have been particularly aware of the inflation rate," he 
said. 
  Tharin said that the inflation was largely caused by 
inadequate good supply, not the government's excessive 
expenditure. "I still believe Thailand will be able to control 
the inflation rate at 4.5 per cent, while the real economic 
growth rate should be 8 per cent on an annual basis," he said. 
Tharin added that he expects the private sector will 
participate more in the investment sector in the near future. 
  "My prime concern, instead, is slower growth in domestic 
savings," Tharin said. He said that he has assigned the Bank of 
Thailand to find out the cause of the marginal growth in 
domestic savings; whether money was transferred to other types 
of investment such as mutual funds and has not been brought back 
into the system. 
  Tharin stressed that the Finance Ministry will keep the 
government's expenditure below Bt[baht]715 billion in 1995. 
Although the government has to spend Bt32 billion on a salary 
rise for civil servants, Tharin said the pay rise is unlikely to 
cause inflation problems. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

