<F P=100> Thailand </F>
<H3> <TI>   Trade Figures With Japan, U.S. in 1993 Released </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Trade Figures With Japan, U.S. in 1993 Released </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK1005055194 Bangkok Radio Thailand Network in English 0000 
GMT 10 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK1005055194 </F>
<F P=104>  Bangkok Radio Thailand Network </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Statistics show that Japan remains Thailand's 
biggest trading partner with bilateral trade volume of 513,000 
million baht in 1993, an increase of 15 percent. 
  The Department of Business Economics says that in 1993, Thai 
exports to Japan accounted for 160,000 million baht, an increase 
of 10 percent. Thailand imported 535,000 [figure as heard] 
million baht from Japan. This represented an increase of 17 
percent, widening Thailand's trade deficit with Japan to 193,000 
million baht. 
  The United States came second in trade relations with 
bilateral trade volume of 338,000 million baht, an increase of 
10 percent over the figure of 1993. The European Union and ASEAN 
came next. Thailand suffered a trade deficit of 17,000 million 
baht with the European Union, while it registered a surplus of 
56,000 million baht and six million baht over the United States 
and ASEAN respectively. 

</TEXT>

