<DOCNO> FBIS4-52329 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas090__a94004" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-090-A </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  10 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Technology Flow to U.S. Raises Concerns </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Technology Flow to U.S. Raises Concerns </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0905105694 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 9 May 
94Morning Edition p 1--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0905105694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The agreement between the Japanese and U.S. 
Governments on a new framework for the exchange of defense 
technology shows that interchangeability between civilian and 
military technology has become a crucial issue in the area of 
defense following the disintegration of the Cold War structure. 
  Senior leaders of the U.S. Defense Department, including 
Secretary of Defense William Perry, show keen interest in the 
proven high level of Japanese civilian technology. They have 
been approaching Japan on this for some time. For the United 
States, which now hopes to promote interchangeability between 
civilian and military technology to strengthen its defense 
industry, while simultaneously reducing the defense budget, the 
introduction of Japanese civilian technology is necessary. 
  For Japan, maintenance of the Japan-U.S. security setup is 
an 
"irrevocable theme" (according to a senior Defense Agency 
official). As bilateral relations are constantly plagued by 
trade frictions, Japan's agreement to this new framework on 
defense technology, which was demanded by the United States, 
represented an "opportune occasion" for upholding close 
cooperation in security and defense. Thus, both countries' 
interests coincided. 
  However, the present agreement will mostly result in a 
technological transfer from Japan to the United States. There 
are concerns that "This may result in the United States alone 
walking away with the benefits." 
  The utilization of civilian technology and exchanges with 
the 
United States are also top priority issues for Japanese 
defense-related industries. These industries mainly look at the 
agreement as a framework for "joint development with both sides 
contributing the technology they possess." There are lingering 
concerns about a one-sided flow of technology to the United 
States. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-52330 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas090__a94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-090-A </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  8 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Zexel To Expand Imports of Auto Parts </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Zexel To Expand Imports of Auto Parts </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0905102894 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 8 May 94 
Morning Edition p 5--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0905102894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Major automobile parts maker Zexel will increase 
annual imports of foreign-made parts to 16 billion yen by 1996, 
which is over 10 times that in 1993. This figure is equivalent 
to 10 percent of the total expenses for materials. Zexel 
decided to change its procurement policy of giving priority to 
domestically made products because quality of foreign-made 
products has improved, in addition to their low prices resulting 
from yen's appreciation. 
  Zexel, which is a primary parts maker, mainly manufactures 
parts of car air conditioners and fuel injection devices, and 
sells these products directly to Nissan Motor Co. Ltd. and Isuzu 
Motors Ltd. So far, it has partially imported compressor parts 
of air conditioners from its U.S. office. The import volume was 
only 1.3 billion yen in 1993, which was less than 1 percent of 
expenses for material procurement. 
  Zexel is now studying the quality and costs of resin 
products, castings, and forgings made by U.S. and Asian makers 
to check whether or not these products are usable. In the case 
of the resin products, they have a quality level similar to that 
of Japanese products, while their prices are 5 to 10 percent 
cheaper. Zexel is likely to start importation in the near 
future. 
  On the other hand, Zexel plans to reduce the number of 
secondary and tertiary parts makers with which it does business. 
Although Zexel has a cooperative organization of subcontracting 
parts makers called "Shineikai," it will conduct stricter 
screening to decide whether to continue doing business with 
those companies. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

