<DATE1>  30 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Interview With SDPJ Chairman Murayama </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Interview With SDPJ Chairman Murayama </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0805121094 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN IN Japanese 30 Apr 
94 Morning Edition p 2--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0805121094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN IN Japanese 30 Apr 
94 Morning Edition p 2--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>




<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with Tomiichi Murayama, chairman of the the </F>
Social Democratic Party of Japan, by NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN; place 
and date not given] 
  [Text] [NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN] How do you plan to deal with 
the new Hata administration? 
  [Murayama] In dealing with each and every issue, we will 
take a free and unbiased approach. Since the Social Democratic 
Party of Japan [SDPJ] has had a part in drawing up the fiscial 
1994 budget, we have our responsibilities toward the people. 
Therefore, we will cooperate with the cabinet in enacting the 
budget and other relevant bills. 
  [NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN] The idea of forming a parliamentary 
group with Sakigake [Harbinger] and other parties has been 
mentioned. What do you think of it? 
  [Murayama] I would give a positive consideration to the 
idea. I would like to have formal talks with Sakigake when the 
long consecutive holidays are over. Topics to be discussed will 
include holding party heads' talks and forming an organ for 
consultations. 
<H5>  SDPJ-LDP Cooperation Is Different From Realignment </H5>
  [NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN] In organizing a parliamentary group, 
will you also consider inviting political parties other than 
Sakigake? 
  [Murayama] We would like to cooperate with anyone, and it 
does not matter whether they belong to the Japan New Party or 
the Democratic Socialist Party [DSP]. We have had troubles with 
the DSP but we were orginal partners in working out plans to get 
all the liberal Social Democrats together. 
  [NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN] How about your relations with the 
Liberal Democratic Party [LDP]? 
  [Murayama] I think we should cooperate with each other in 
promoting the Diet operations. However, it has to be separated 
from the issue on regrouping of political parties. In other 
words, the point at issue lies in how various political forces 
will be regrouped. And in actually promoting the Diet 
operations, we will cooperate with the LDP on all the issues on 
which we can cooperate with each other. 
  [NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN] Following the enactment of the budget 
bill, the LDP may call for a no-confidence vote in the cabinet. 
In that case, will the SDPJ act in concert? 
  [Murayama] It would be desirable to make the decision 
depending on the actual political situation at the time. At 
present, Japan is suffering from economic stagnation and we have 
various serious problems in both domestic and foreign affairs, 
with the major one being our relations with the United States. 
Therefore, it is preferable not to create a political vaccum at 
the moment. However, if the new cabinet should come to a 
deadlock and the only alternative left for the cabinet to break 
the deadlock is to dissolve the lower house, then I would say 
there is no other choice. 
Having Signed the Policy Accord, SDPJ Still Has Its 
Responsibilities [subhead] 
  [NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN] Among the major policy tasks, how do 
you intend to tackle the tax reforms issue? 
  [Murayama] Since the SDPJ did sign the policy accord in 
forming the new coalition government the other day, we still 
have our responsibilities. Our activities will no longer be 
restricted because we are no longer a member of the ruling 
coalition. However, it does not follow that we will start anew 
with a completely clean slate. 
  [NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN] You will not change your position of 
tolerating an increase in the indirect tax rate. Is that right? 
  [Murayama] It should be based on the drastic revision of 
inequalities in the tax system and on reduction of the 
government expenditures. However, if the government should 
clearly indicate the amount of funds needed for promoting 
welfare measures for the country's aging population in the 
future, and then explain that revenues gained from increased 
indirect taxes will be used for this purpose, then I am sure it 
will be able to win the people's understanding about the tax 
reform. The point at issue lies in abruptly starting to 
increase the current consumption tax rate. No opposition has 
been voiced within our party to efforts to correct the ratio 
between direct and indirect taxes. 
  [NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN] When will the SDPJ work out its 
final conclusion? 
  [Murayama] Since the party's tax system research council has 
already worked out guidelines, we would like to conduct 
full-scale intraparty discussions on the basis of these 
guidelines. I think our party plan will be worked out as early 
as in June when the ruling parties are going to work out their 
conclusions. 
<H5>  SDPJ Split Is Impossible </H5>
  [NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN] How does the SDPJ plan to deal with 
the issue of suspected nuclear arms development by DPRK (North 
Korea)? 
  [Murayama] What is most important is to resolve this issue 
through talks. If there is anything that the SDPJ can be of 
service, we will do our best. Depending on the situation, a 
delegation may be dispatched to the DPRK. When we were a member 
of the ruling coalition, our activities were restricted. Now, 
we can act on the basis of our independent decision. 
  [NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN] In the course of regrouping political 
parties or in dealing with major policies, is there any 
possibility that the intraparty confrontation between the 
rightist and leftist factions will become intensified? 
  [Murayama] There are various policy groups within the party. 
In the sense that they contribute to promoting the party's 
vitality, it is most desirable. However, it will be undesirable 
if their activities should go beyond the party's framework and 
lead to the split of the party. It should be noted that the 
whole party has taken concerted action in seceding from the 
coalition this time. Therefore, it is impossible for the SDPJ 
to split. 
  [NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN] Have you been considering any 
measures to increase the strength of the party executives? 
  [Murayama] We intend to give a briefing on the future course 
the party should take and once again call for achieving party 
unity at the Central Executive Committee session scheduled for 
late May. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

